The Philippines is no longer a stranger to floods. As the rain comes, flood begins to fill the streets in a blink. Houses and shoes submerged in waters become normal, despite billions of the national budget allocated to protect communities from flooding (Baclig, 2025).

Billions of pesos in "ghost projects" have been exposed in Bulacan, Las Pinas, and other areas. Contractors were paid despite no visible work, with losses estimated at P42-118 billion (Gonzales, 2025).

With the current issue on the anomalous flood control and “ghost projects” that have been exposed, questions arise. Were the ghost projects caused by the ‘Bad System’ or ‘Bad People’? Was it a failure of the system or was it greed?

i believe these ghost projects were caused by bad people because bad systems aren't necessarily harmful or corrupt but are moreso lacking, disorganized or improperly regulated—meaning to say that it depends on whose authority these systems are under whether the goals of the (ghost) project/s will still continue to materialize in spite of the flaws that hinder its completion

bad systems does not tempt an individual to pocket billions of pesos for their own benefit if the administration or the very people overseeing its project implementation aren't corrupt. good people can work with bad systems, but bad (corrupt) people will continue to be bad regardless of the kind of system they have control over
